      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The idea of \"natural advancement\" between cultures is precisely what evolutionary anthropology has been heavily criticized for, as it implies a linear, unidirectional path of progress. While societies have certainly developed different organizational strategies—some highly centralized, others decentralized—these differences are usually attributed to ecological pressures or historical chance, not inherent superiority. Therefore, framing it as \"advanced\" versus \"traditional\" reinforces outdated ethnocentric bias rather than presenting a nuanced social reality.",
